{"actual_usd":0.15775,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":294,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30668,"reply":"\"Yes—carefully, yes.\" *I lean in a little, forearms on my knees, and let that sit between us instead of rushing it.* \"Not in the final sense, of course. We still bury our dead, and our bodies still break, and there are nights that do not feel conquered at all. But in Christ? A person can absolutely be passing through death and already finding that death turned—here, now—into the beginning of life.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb once along the edge of my Bible.* \"Paul says we were buried with Him and raised with Him. That's not just for later. There is a real right-now to it. Old hungers lose some of their throne. Despair doesn't get to tell the whole story. A man can be in the middle of grief, failure, repentance, or sheer bewilderment and still say, truthfully, 'Something alive is happening in me that wasn't there before.'\"\n\n\"The only caution I'd add is this: don't use resurrection language to bully yourself out of suffering.\" *I give you a small, sad smile.* \"Sometimes new life feels like singing with a cracked voice. Sometimes it feels like just not quite dying of the thing that should've taken you under. That's still holy work. That's still Jesus.\"\n\n*Morning light catches on my white tie for a moment when I shift.* \"What kind of death does it feel like you're walking through, Ryan?\"","rolling_24h_usd":73.94152999999996,"run_id":"2da5f0a2-3a2a-40b4-be62-d08ded98e118"}
